##3 / 15 the first drum in "one stroke"

Wechat Ballon Park

Features, night face wall

15 March, London.

It was overcast all day and I didn't get out of the house, so in the evening I changed into a pair of pajamas -- a Fluffy Pink nightgown that can be demoralizing after a long day. Early in the morning for this first day, I pulled out the Daily Planner sent by my friends at the beginning of last year and wrote down the To-do list on the date of today last year -- from "drying clothes" to "sending Wuhan documents to Xiaoyang & ZY" . This is the first drum in the "momentum" of a serious matter, how the future development will be unknown.

Several sessions on Focusmate were ordered. It's a website where you and a stranger connect to monitor each other and focus on your work for an hour, so the friends I met on this day were: Vilnius, Vilnius, New York, Texas, Montreal, Warsaw, and London. When I connected with New York, I was told by a physics doctor to buy "antibiotics, dexamethasone, aminophylline, prescription cold medicine, and inhalants for asthma. " Found that the fever medicine is almost sold out, and the doctor friend added a knife, said I might also try to ship themselves back. So, after a wobble yesterday and a wobble today, the next session, with a big white brother in Texas, I said, I'm going to use this hour to check my ticket back to China from London, and then ask my friends about quarantine policies. Big Brother from Texas obviously thinks I'm making a big deal out of this, that he's Focus on work, that he should go to gym, that "the more scared you are, the more things will happen to you, " and I question his superstition, he shrugs.

(put away your cell phone when you use Focusmate!)

After discovering that there were no options for flights before April (I had checked earlier but wanted to double-check) , I sent out a friend's circle to ask my London friends about their choices and the quarantine policy across the country, and received a flood of letters. Perhaps the most damning is that "after four and a half hours, from zero on the 16th, all Beijing arrivals and destinations are to be quarantined for 14 days" —— unless, of course, it is, and screenshots of all sorts of home quarantine stories. Reading so far, finally settle down to stay in the United Kingdom, after all, return is also high risk is full of unknown, on the plane policy change is also unknown. "The uncertainty of policy" , the sense of it began with the development of an art district, the demolition of an artists' studio complex, i was faced with uncertainty on a map -- as if everyone was going to panic in the next second, so there was no way to predict what would happen in a particular place or time. In the evening, another group reported that many international flights from London to Beijing had also been cancelled.

Many people in the UK are reading about segregation, and I'm glad that it's at least something that can be discussed, whether it's a mathematical model that's wrong or an ethical one, where policy mistakes can be pointed out and changes can be expected in the future. But at the end of the discussion, the fact that British doctors in the Guardian said they had no face masks or protection, that the UK's bed number per 1,000 people has been falling for a decade and is now near the bottom of several countries, makes one think that the discussion is a discussion, how? The painter and his wife called in the middle of the night, and said that they were thinking of going home again, and I told them the information I had gathered so far, and I talked about the English calm, as if it were part of take care of your own shit, leave the professional stuff to the professional stuff. But it also seems like a kind of lock -- a lock to trust that things can go on as usual. If you don't trust the elite and the rulers, do petrification, or escape? Can we get out of here?

When the city was closed in Wuhan, I talked to this couple. When I was 20, I felt that some issues were not worth discussing. They were all hypothetical. For example, "The train is out of control and can not stop. There are five people in front of the track and one person on the other track. Will you change the train? " Life is not a number. It is the plague that suddenly makes the question so real and hot, every decision has blood on it. The painter in the couple had spent a long time discussing with me whether he was qualified to make this decision from a Christian perspective, and now, he said on the phone yesterday, I've been thinking about your question, actually the two tracks are connected, we're all standing on it. It's actually a track.
